nomic foundations upon which rest the global political economy and institutional architecture. It remains to be seen how the size of the emerging powers translates into the ability to shape the international system to their own will. In this book, leading international relations experts examine the positions and roles of key emerging countries in the potential transformation of the G8 and the prospects for their deeper engagement in international governance. The essays consider a number of overlapping perspectives on the G8 Heiligendamm Process, a co-operation agreement that originated from the 2007 summit, and offer an in-depth look at the challenges and promises presented by the rise of the emerging powers. Co-published with the Centre for International Governance Innovation  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInternational cooperation. 0aInternational organization. 0aInternational relations. 4aPolitical Science. 4aPolitical Science: Globalization. 4aPolitical Science: International Relations. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / General.2bisacsh1 aAlexandroff, Alan S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntkiewicz, Agata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntkiewicz, Agata, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBowles, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradford, Colin I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChin, Gregory T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Andrew F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Andrew F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFues, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregory, Denise,